segments.text: This is July 29, 1987.
We're in the dean's conference room at Texas A&M.
I'm interviewing Chewie Hinojosa.
OK.
I first got involved with Texas A&M University back in 1954 when I came here as a student.
I was in general studies at the time and trying to find a career or curriculum that would interest me.
During the career day of that year, I was able to look around the university and saw that the work in the Department of Architecture interested me and felt that I could do it and enjoy it.
Where were you living at that time?
Originally, I came from south Texas in the little town of Ed Couch in the lower Rio Grande Valley.
It's about 20 miles from the Mexican border and about 50 miles inland from the Texas Gulf Coast.
You were up here for a career day.
Actually, I was already enrolled at A&M as a student at the time, yeah.
How did that happen?
Why did you choose A&M?
Oh, A&M, yes.
Well, my father talked to a friend of his he knew who had a feet store there in Edcouch, and he was an A&M graduate.
And so he asked him if he would suggest any university that I might go to after I graduated from high school, after getting ready to graduate from high school.
So he, you know, Nagy, he recommended Texas A&M.
He thought it was a good school.
And so that was how I happened to select A&M, you know.
And then you came up for career day.
No.
And I just applied.
to the university at the time.
It was a college, Texas A&M College.
Sight unseen.
Yes, sight unseen, just based on catalogs and whatever I could get in the mail from them after I decided to inquire about the university and decided to come to A&M.
And so they accepted my enrollment based on the normal procedures for enrolling.
It wasn't until I was here for about a year, almost a year, that I didn't know what to enroll in, basically.
I just enrolled in a general engineering curriculum.
And after about three quarters of the year, I wasn't really doing well.
And I actually was in the Corps for one year.
And it was a miserable experience, because we really couldn't study.
Yeah.
Was it mandated to be in the Corps at that time?
Actually, interestingly enough, at the time,
A new president had been hired by him who was not an Aggie.
I believe his name was Morgan, President Morgan, if I remember correctly.
And he, being, I believe, from the East, had requested and had gotten approval to make the Corps optional at the time.
But when I enrolled, since all the literature was kind of geared to the Corps, and I was a member of the Texas National Guard at the time,
I think it will be something like that.
I did enjoy some discipline and kind of the rigors of the military and order and all that.
That appealed to me.
But when we landed here in the first weekend after we had been here for about a week in orientation,
We lost about 15 or 20 freshmen that first weekend because of the crazy, I mean, this is like, they were going out to West Point, that's what they were trying to do.

Interestingly enough, also, I guess part of the psychology was that the upperclassmen could not touch us physically because it had also been mandated that you could not touch a student physically, physically haze them because they had had some problems in the past.
And they had some after that, too.
Yes.
They had some brothers afterwards, too.
And so they had given strict orders they would not touch a student physically.
So they launched a psychological warfare, which is probably worse.
Yeah.
Because they really, it was a reign of terror on us all the time, constantly, constantly.
And if I remember correctly, the numbers out of, I think our outfit had 120 freshmen.
And there were about 60 of us left by the middle of the school year.
And all of us were just barely hanging in there grade-wise and so forth.
And then about the end of the year, about 30 of us was left in the outfit.
And so I said, well, this is not really what I'm looking for.
I mean, I came to study.
I didn't feel I needed all this exorbitant discipline.
But we couldn't study.
We couldn't eat.
I went home.
They thought I was some kind of a refugee.
I lost weight.
I wasn't that heavy to begin with.
My hair was cut short.
I looked like I had come out of Huntsville.
So I said, well, I don't need this.
And since the Corps was optional, I went ahead and finished out the year.
I felt, OK, I'll finish out my commitment for that year that I had agreed to do.
And the next year, I went civilian still.

And also, because I had used the career days and opportunity to look around, and I believe in career days for that reason, because it did help me to kind of see the opportunities that were available to me as a student here.
I did go around all the different departments that they
And when I got to the fourth floor of the academic building where the architecture school used to be, I immediately sensed that I could relate to the work and to the environment and everything else.
So I made my decision quickly, and I said, okay, that's what I'm going to do.
I'm going to change curriculums coming at the end of the school year and when I enroll for the next year.
Who was the dean?
Yeah, I guess an interesting anecdote.
I was counsel.
I had to go through counseling because I was just barely scraping by with a C average.
And the counselor, after they did all the testing and everything else, told me that I had no aptitude for architecture and anything related to the field.
But interesting enough, the following year, I was a distinguished student.
My grade points shot up very high.
And I managed to get on the dean's list as a distinguished student.
And from there on, it was fine.
I enjoyed the program and everything else.
I really felt that I was doing what I wanted to do.
And then during that year, we had various people visiting lectures that came to the university.
It was a good lecture program.
We had a good lecture series.
And I met different people from around this country.
And I got to know other faculty in the advanced years.
I got to know Joe McGraw, who was then a design professor, and Professor Edward Romanek, who was also the director of the design studios.
And they sort of were, they took me under their wing so that they could help me along and gave me encouragement.

And then I got to meet, well, I visualized myself finishing architecture and going to, you know, work actually, work for a firm and going to architectural practice and hopefully eventually get my license and all that business.
But during the last year or so, I then got interested, of course, in teaching and they
Professor Ramegan-McGraw encouraged me if I would be interested in teaching.
They needed some faculty, so I taught for three years.
And during that time, they had some guest speakers.
And one of them was Reginald Isaacs from Harvard.
And he had been in South America and was on his way back to Harvard when they had asked him if he would lecture here.
So he came and lectured at A&M at the time.
And so we visited and we talked.
And so he indicated that he would be interested in my applying at Harvard.
in planning.
And so I did that later, and I was accepted.
And so after working for one summer at Caudill Rowland Scott, and actually worked with Bill Caudill that particular summer, it was an interesting experience in itself.
Great guy.
I really enjoyed working with him, and he was really an inspiration.
I then came back and taught for two years at A&M, and then applied at Harvard, and got accepted, and went for two years in the graduate planning program.
I got my master's in city planning there.
What year?
That was in 62, went from 62 to 1964.
I taught from 60 to 62, I'm sorry, here in architecture.
Then I worked in Houston the summer of 1960, and I worked in Harold Hamilton's office in Dallas in the summer of 63.
So then in, I'm sorry, in 1961.
Then in 1962, and then I went to Harvard until 64.
And there I got a job.
I'm sorry, well, after I finish, rather, I interviewed some people from California and had gotten a job, actually a job offer.
I interviewed with a firm representative from a firm in San Francisco, Warneke, John Carl Warneke's firm.
He had been out to the East Coast and was interviewing at different schools.
And so I was introduced to him.
That's interesting, because I was working in his office.
Really?
Yeah.
Well, they were setting up a planning department, actually, within the architecture firm at the time, and they needed somebody to help them set it up.
They left their libraries and their expertise in planning.
So I did, and we got off well, and so I got everything packed, and I took off, went home to see my parents, and then I drove in a little Ford Falcon
all the way to California in the middle of the hottest summer I can imagine.
When we hit Southern California, it was 110 or 120 degrees, something like that.
Anyway, I survived the trip and got to California.
But when I got to San Francisco, this gentleman I had interviewed with told me, I have a very interesting job assignment for you.
And so I said, let's talk about it.
So I did.
I had got myself checked in.
And he wanted to send me to Hawaii.
And I said, well, I don't know.
I said, I was interested in coming out to California, because I've heard so much about California.
I wanted to really get to know California, San Francisco area, the whole stadium.
So I wasn't too keen on that.
So I managed to contact, I was kind of in the process of making an arrangement to ship my car and everything to Hawaii.
And I just, by luck, happened to call a former professor of mine, Professor Joseph J. McGraw, who at the time had also, before that even had gone to California, was working in California.
And I sort of kept some correspondence with him, and I just thought I'd say hello and see how he was doing.
And so he said, well, what are you doing out here on the West Coast?
I said, I didn't realize you were interested in coming out to the West Coast.
He said, well, I wasn't either.
I just sort of thought I would.

And so he started telling me what he was doing, who he was working with in this fairly large firm in the Bay Area, and that there were native people, and that if I was interested in working for their firm,
I could have a job, you know.
And so he offered me a position in their firm.
And he explained the kind of work that the firm did.
It was an architecture, engineering, and planning firm.
And so I said, well, I don't know.
I have to check with these people first because I already made my commitments to them.
So once I could not change them, he gave me an assignment in San Francisco office, in Wernicke's office.
I decided then to go with, at the time, it was Woolsey, Hamm, and Blair, fairly large firm in California.
And I started working on a Sunday afternoon.
They were so busy at the time.
California was an incredibly busy state at the time.
That was 1962?
This was in 1964.
Right.
At Foster City.
In 1964, the firm had built the first building in the new town called Foster City, which was sort of an invention building into the Bay Area.
It had been approved, of course, and so forth.
By Jack Foster from Texas.
Yes.
Yes, I didn't realize his origin.
That's where we met.
That's right.

We were working with William Blair, and it was an interesting operation because we had, I think, a very unique setup of planners, engineers, architects working together in interdisciplinary teams, which I have believed in.
See, Joe McGraw was there, and Jim Gardner.
Did he arrive later?
I'm not quite sure.
Jim, I think, arrived later, yeah.
And Matt Copenhaver.
Matt Copenhaver was there.
Dick Ehrenberger was there.
Let's see who else did we play.
Well, that's enough talent for one firm.
It was a very interesting group, actually.
And the development design department, which we called 3D department, was an interesting department because we brought all these people together into a team.
And we did the preliminary work and the selling of the studies to clients.
And then the preliminary concepts were hammered out by this group.
And then they were passed on to the other individuals for the surveying and the actual engineering and cost estimates and so forth.
So it made for an interesting combination.

After having been with the firm for actually, I guess it was less than a year, they decided to encourage me to continue with the firm by giving me a bonus at the end of the year, which they seldom gave to anybody who was with the firm less than a year.
And the guys said they were in a real quandary about it.
So I felt good about that.
I felt I wanted to continue with this firm.
And they, in fact, gave me more responsibilities and larger assignments.
I got to work on the
Southside's plan with it for the big developer, Dolger, Mr. Dolger, who had done basically built all of that stuff.
South San Francisco.
South San Francisco area after the war, which made the Tiki-Taki house famous.
He's the guy who actually built them.
You had a hand in that.
No, I did not have a hand in the Tiki-Takis.
I did have an interesting experience meeting the man, because he was a very interesting fellow, actually.

He was a very down-to-earth guy, and he felt that he was meeting and addressing a need that wasn't being met by anybody else for low- and middle-income families, especially after the war when there was an
with a high shortage of housing.

And one of his policies, an interesting one that he had at the time he was building houses in South San Francisco area was that he would put a tree in front of every house as a minimum in the landscaping and so forth.
So we went back and drove around this area.
And it really looked kind of decent, even though it was kind of high density.
Houses were packed in kind of tight, to be sure.
But he had kept up a fairly attractive quality development after all.

In the new area that we were working in, the 25,000 acre that we were working with him now, that was definitely a quality development, and he wanted that, and he wanted to set a good standard, and it was a beautiful area of the county.
How long were you with Woolsey Hammond, Blair?
Well, I was there in the area about a year and a half, and then at the end of 1965, they had gotten some assignments in South America, and they had put some teams together to send
When the projects came in, they didn't have anybody to send.
Everybody backed out.
They didn't want to go for some reason or another.
Yeah, so then I had the opportunity of my life.
The vice president said they needed to send someone to take care of some very substantial projects in Chile.
There was a program, actually, by the Chilean government to start planning in the country, establish planning in the country.
They were doing national planning, regional planning, and local planning.
And our job was to develop the local planning end of it.

And in order to do national planning, they felt they needed to have more information at the local level in order to bring together all the plans and therefore use those to put together the national budgets for different categories of investments.
I think that I had left and had taken a leave of absence from the firm before you left for Chile.
and had gone with the Association of Bay Area Governments.
That's right.
You were in transition to go to Association of Bay Area Governments.
That was all because of my thesis.
Oh, really?
Which was on regional planning in the Bay Area.
I see.
Well, that was certainly the place to go at the time.
Yeah, it was a good move.

Yeah, it was an impressive operation at AIPAC, and I had a little knowledge of it, of course, because we had to do some relating our own local planning in the area, and we were very conscious of what they were trying to do.
coordinate the whole Bay region was an impressive project.
And to this day, it seems to be an impressive effort.
We had pretty good support from the federal government.
Oh, yes.
It was a big effort.
I think certainly that also led to the creation of the Association of Bay Area Governments, of course, which brought unity between county cities and the state.
A lot of large-scale projects had to be coordinated at that level.
It couldn't be done otherwise without that agency.
I think it created an awareness of the area as a region, which resulted in the Bay Conservation and Development Commission.
I was going to say, that then was a follow-up with the Conservation Commission.
And the California Coastal Zone Commission.
Right.
And that was also forerunners of many of the coastal zone management and large area management, regional management programs we have since come to know.
Well, back to Chile.
You were down there, and how long were you in Chile?
Well, I was there for two and a half years.
Two and a half years.
And you finished your work, and then you came back to Wolseyham and Blair?
After I finished the work there, they wanted me to come back to the...
San Francisco office, San Mateo office.
But at the time, I had been in correspondence with Professor McGraw, who had expressed an interest in my coming back.
He had left Wilson, Hammond, Blair, I believe, about a year before I left to go to Chile, approximately.

And he had been offered a job over here at Texas A&M University to head the planning program because they had, actually, when he was here in architecture, they had proposed a planning program, and it was not approved.
But it had finally gotten approved around the middle 60s.
And so he was asked if he would come and have that program.
So he had done that in, I believe it was in 65 when he came to establish it.
And so I had been in Chile for two and a half years, so that would be 68.
So I think by then, Joe had been working on the program for two or three years, something to that effect.
And so he needed faculty and had asked me if I would join the faculty.
I think that Jim Gardner was already here.
I think Jim, yes, had left the California firm and had come over to the department.
Yes, by then he was here too, that's right.
So you were the third faculty member in the planning department.
I believe so, because when did you come here?
I came after you were here.
Okay, so that would be right then.
Yeah, I came in the fall of 1969.
Okay, that's right.
I came here in the fall of 68, so about a year apart.
It was a young program.
It was a new program.

It had been established and had gone through the first three years that were required by, at the time, APA for recognition and had met those requirements and had the kind of recognition that was required at the time.
So that was the first program instead of Texas, actually.
A recognized program instead of Texas.
So it was an exciting experience to come back to the University.
I never thought I would come back to A&M.
And I was, you know, first teaching here, a student, but it was a good experience to come back.
We had an exciting program.
Okay, well then, what were your ideas at that time, or did you remember what your ideas were on planning education?
Did you, had you any philosophy that had developed through your practice?
Yeah, well, the practice had been certainly valuable to alert me to the
the realities of the world out there.
In Chile, I really learned a lot about planning trial by fire, so to speak, because I was alone 7,000 miles away from my home office.
And although we had really top-notch people looking over my shoulder, like Francis from Berkeley, who was a special consultant.
He was down there.
Well, he was at Berkeley, but he went down there once during the process, or twice.
But he had been in Latin America for many years before that, so he knew the country well and a lot of the people there.
And he was a recognized international consultant in Latin America, and actually elsewhere, too, in Europe.
And so he was a good guide.
And then we had other people from the firm.
Still, such great business communications weren't that great.
You oftentimes had to act without complete guidance
always having the answers there from your superiors and so forth.
So I had to really look up a lot of the stuff I had studied in school and reread it and reconsider it in the light of the actual practice.
They've had so much political turmoil in Chile.
How did that affect your work?
Well, it was at times rough because we were outsiders at the time.
This was at the height of the Vietnam War, and anti-Americanism was running pretty high in some of these countries.
The Communist Party and some of the other socialist parties were pretty powerful there in that part of the world.
Oh, excuse me.
I'm sorry.
Yeah, these groups were very outspoken.
And, of course, the Frey administration at the time was trying to open up democracy in the country and really provide a democratic environment.
So it did permit a lot of outspokenness on the part of opposition parties.
There was a dialogue always going on in the newspapers, in the media, news media, and so forth.
It was a very interesting experience because Chile was a tug-of-war with Cuba because Castro's Cuba had become a challenge to the United States, hegemony in the area.
They were using Chile as a way of saying there was another way to go about democratizing these countries.
You don't have to always use force.
that there can be a positive approach through democratic procedures.

And so President Frey was trying to slowly Chileanize a lot of the things that were actually, a lot of the big companies and the big corporations that were owned by outside interests, American and European interests.
the big mining copper mines and so forth, which really were the backbone of the country's economy, were really owned by outsiders.
They had really no say in the matter, very little say in the matter, in fact.
I understand a lot of British interests were there.
Yes, they were very strong.
The British interest was also very strong in the mining and the phosphate mines and the copper mines as well.
And when the price of copper folded, they just left.
Yes, it just packed up and left everything.
Exactly.
And the country, you see, depended on income from copper.
That was their main moneymaker for the country.
So during the war, of course, this was a big income generator.
And so it heightened the need by Chileans, who were very much nationalists, of course.
And there's nationalists that we can get about our own country.
They wanted their country to have some control over their key resources on which the country depended to be able to set some policy for national development.
Exactly, instead of having to just pack up and leave you whenever they want to, you know, have something that was a little more consistent.
And also to have a little more say about the procedures for mining and how the resources would be utilized.
Well, it's insulting not to.
Oh, yes.
And I could see, and that was a very important learning experience for me, I could see
why there was so much anti-Americanism developing in this region of the world, because they could see the ugly American coming in there and taking over a lot of these investments.
And while it's important, I don't want to minimize the effort on the part of the American investor.
I think it's an important thing.
It's a risky venture, and it takes a lot of gumption to do it, too.
And that's good, and I think that should be encouraged.
I also think that a lot of times they were able to corrupt local officials
who would manipulate their position and their position, the arrangement, in such a manner that the country was being, as a whole, left out of the picture.

And this is what, while it may have sounded like an innocent thing at the time it was occurring, this occurred, of course, way back in the turn of the century, and even before the end of the century, when us states were really important to the country.
This engendered, this animosity began to build up, and it really surfaced in the 60s.
And the Vietnam War really brought all this out to the surface.
And we had tremendous, of course, tug-of-war going on around the world at the time.

So it was an interesting experience for me because I saw my country from a distance, and I appreciated the United States even more from a distance, because I think it's the greatest country in the world to this day, even with all its mistakes and flaws.
But I also saw how we could do a lot more and be a lot better partners, so to speak, in development.

So the planning we were doing, we were motivated, of course, to do good planning so that these communities could be planned for appropriately and the resources be used carefully so they could have a better environment for their housing areas and their commercial areas and their various needs for public services.
And that was a challenge we were opposed with.

And the planning was very much part of the political arm of the Frey administration because all this was being done, of course, to show that they could work efficiently and produce a good environment for the population.
and complement whatever the social services they were trying to develop through good planning.
So it had that dimension to it.
So we were obviously thrust into a political environment automatically.
Everything we did had political implications.
I had some interesting experience in the southern part of the country, because there was some enclaves over there of communists and socialists.
There were very strong anti-American feelings.
I had an interesting experience because being of Latin extraction, Mexican-American, Mexican extraction, a lot of times these people didn't know who I was.
They thought I was Chilean, they thought I was Peruvian, they thought I was Central American.
Could they tell by your accent?
No.
Apparently, I picked up their own language so quickly.
Within about three or four or six months, I was talking like they were.
I used their terms, all their colloquialisms.
At times, they thought I was Chilean.
Chile's a heterogeneous country.
It's very cosmopolitan in the first place.
Like Argentina.
Very much so, yeah.
Very, very well-educated people.
Good-sized middle class.
The best professionals you can find are in Chile and Argentina, yeah.
I think the climate has a lot to do with that.
They're in a temperate zone.
Yes, they are.
And I guess they had a good stock of migrations from Spain and Europe, Germany, and so forth.
They did have a pretty strong cadre of professional middle-class groups.
And the countries are very strong for that reason.
They have tremendous capability.
So I had the opportunity to prepare two general development plans, one for the city of Puerto Montt, which is the extreme south part of the country.
It's a very interesting environment.
Better spell it.
Better spell it.
Yes, Porto Montt, yeah, P-U-E-R-T-O, and then another word, M-O-N-T-T, which I believe is a German word.
It's a German name of a family name in Chile.
This port is the last major port on the mainland of Chile before you start the fjords that go all the way down to the southern tip of the continent.
The continent fragments itself with a bunch of islands and so forth, fjords.
Down to Tierra del Fuego, where the Fuegans live.
Right.
Down to Antarctica, which they claim a little slice of.
And so Puerto Montt was the main port and the first port that a ship would make at the rounding Cape Horn.
Tierra del Fuego, yes.
And so it was always a thriving port, major regional capital.
It still remains a major regional capital, but it lost some of its economic strength when the Panama Canal was built and the shipping then didn't have to go always around the Cape.
However, it used to be an important port, so we did the planning.
And they also suffered from earthquakes.
And this has been a tremendous problem for them.
So when we were there, I was doing the planning.
We started the work in 66, somewhere in there.
They had suffered some earthquakes before in 50 and in, I believe, 62, somewhere in there.
And they were rebuilding the port and other facilities.
And so I found a lot of geologic information
that was put together by the U.S. Geologic Survey and other international groups.
And I found that in California, interestingly enough, before I left to go to Chile.
And I had this information with me, and we used it in the planning.
We looked at the soils, and we looked at the location of faults, fault lines, and used this information to locate the new residential areas and the new
public facilities and so forth, trying to avoid the dangerous soils and so forth.
And so it was a beginning of integration of the spatial, physical aspects with these danger areas as identified by the geologists.
And what was the other city?
The other city following was the city of Osorno.
Osorno, O-S-O-R-N-O, is the capital also of a province of Yankeewe.
And it's an interesting city because it concentrates a large number of German population.
that came over in the late 1800s, settlers to help settle that part of the country.
Did they speak Spanish?
Yes, a lot of them did, in fact, speak Spanish.
It was kind of curious to see a tall, six foot three or four, blond, with blue eyes, speaking Chilean, and with a German name.
And a lot of prominent German names in the rural countryside.
I think they speak mostly German.
A lot of the old families still just speak German.
And so it's an interesting project because it's the most dynamic province in the country.
It has the strongest economy.
It has a diversified economic base.
It has agriculture and it has a milk processing product type industry.
It has leather goods products industries and so forth.
They've used this to diversify their economy base.
In Osorno, they also produce the best beef in the country and have exported throughout the country.
And when I was in Chile, because of the meat shortages, we had to ration beef.
You could only buy it one time a week on Friday, usually Friday afternoons.
And in Santiago, for example, the capital city, you could only eat meat once a week.
But in Osorno, they ate meat every day because they produced it and they weren't about to ration themselves.
As a Catholic country, I would think they would have sold fish on Friday.
Yes, yes, right.
That's true.
No, I think the people did, too, do that, yes.
But because of the rationing, then Friday became a very important day for acquiring meat, even though it was a Catholic country.
They also promoted whale meat, interestingly enough, because of this.
Again, it was a problem of cash flows.
So anyway, we did the work, and we completed the studies.
So Sorna was a very interesting experience because the mayor was very dynamic.
Not German expression, he was a Spanish type, but very well-liked, very dynamic guy.
He had a broad support, political support.
He's probably the most dynamic politician I've gone into, you know.

He managed to bring diverse groups together, and it made the planning very interesting for that same reason, because we did have a good, clear guide on what was critical and what they felt was priority.
So the planning was, he gave us an office, and they had a 12-story office building.
That was their municipal building that they financed, and they rented the lower floors for offices to get income to pay for the building.
They had office spaces, and they gave us office space.
They gave us personnel to do all our work, you know,
So it was a very well-run thing.
Of course, it was a great advantage for you being able to speak Spanish.
Yes, that was very helpful, definitely.
And I think if they had sent a consultant they had initially intended to, which would not be people that were well versed in the language, they would have a very hard time completing the assignments.
I would think so.
Because of the political pressure, we only had literally 321 days to finish the assignments.
That was seven months.
That was calendar days, not working days.
A job that I estimated would take 18 months to finish in California with all the funding and resources available, we had to do in seven months in Chile.
So it was very intense, very intense.
And so I was blessed with good colleagues.
We had good local professionals that helped and formed part of the team.
So I was the only one, well, two of us from the firm.
Sounds like you had good political leadership.
Yeah.
Yeah, very much so.
And so we did well, and the ministry appreciated our work because we did a good piece of work.
It was an interesting experience because, see, when we came, we were the only outside firm.
All the rest were Chilean firms.
There were no, except for one Chilean firm that had some planning, could claim planning experience.
Everybody else were just basically architectural firms.
So part of the task was not only to do the job, but to teach and to transmit the idea of planning
to the local people and to the local professionals.

And so we were always, when we first, of course, showed up on the scene, we said, oh, here comes this guy from the U.S., from California, and they're going to want to propose, you know, the moon, everything's going to cost, you know, this harebrained solutions to the problem.
But interestingly enough, as our stay there continued and we developed the project,
Our projects were the most reasonable and the most realistic in terms of the local economy and the availability of funds and the feasibility of getting them done.
And, in fact, one day we were called in by the ministry to
They wanted to find out why, except that there were no complaints coming out of Osorno about us, when they were getting complaints out of everybody else from around the country.
And they wanted to know why.
And so I explained that we worked very closely with the mayor, very closely with the council, the governor, and the local community officials.
And you probably realized what the state of the technology was.
Yes, and that was the California experience.
We learned that in California, because the citizen participation was important, getting people involved early in the process and keeping them informed.
So we took that over there, and it worked, and we gave reasonable solutions to complicated problems that we felt they could afford within their budgets.
While the other guys were producing some very, I mean, L.A. was...

Okay, of course, coming back from Chile, although the firm had wanted me to go back to California, they wanted me to continue with the firm, I had been offered a job at Texas A&M University, Professor McGraw, and Edward, at the time, was... Edward Romanek.
Well, Professor McGraw was the director of the planning program here.
And Professor Edward Romnick was the dean, yes, at the time.
R-O-M-I-E-N-I-E-C.
Right.
R-O-M-I-E-N-I-E-C. And Edward Romnick was the dean, and Joe McGraw was the department program chairman.
So they invited me if I would join the faculty.
They wanted to expand the faculty.
I think they had also an interest in the Latin American region.
What year was that?
That was in 68.
I came back in the middle of 68.
So I started in the fall of 68.
Were you married then?
No, I was single.
I got married the following year in 1969.
In fact, on my way through here to say hello to my friends and introduce my new bride, we ran into the situation of a

contract had been sent, or another contract, but a proposal, rather, a request for proposal had been sent to the university, to Jim Gardner, who then had joined the planning faculty, Professor Gardner.
From Wilsey, Hammond, Blair.
Who had been also at Wilsey, Hammond, Blair before in California.
And Mr. Stan Ott.
With McGraw and Cornish and Hinojosa.
Yeah, right.
I always call it the finishing school of planners.
We all had gone through it and had gotten good experience out of it.

And then Stanley Ott, who we knew, both of us knew, you and I knew at San Mateo, who had been planning director there, had got an assignment with USAID, the United States Agency for International Development, in Colombia.
And so he sent this request proposal to Jim Gardner, whom he knew,
and inquiring if we would be interested in responding to it by providing technical assistance in planning to the city of Cali, the second largest city in the country of Colombia.
And so Jim Garner passed the document to me asking if I would be interested because it would require someone with the language capability and the interest in the Latin American region and so forth.
And so myself and Tom Stallworth, Thomas Stallworth who was a local professional who had just finished the planning program and was a civil engineer but a very, very interesting person,
and had an interest in the Latin American region, the two of us got together and responded to the request.

So we sent back, we prepared the request, the response to the request for the proposal, and I took it with me, and on the road, on my honeymoon, I mailed it, I think, out of California after I finished all the questions they wanted answers to, and mailed it, signed it, and mailed it.
And then when we get back about three weeks later, there was a cable that came in,
saying that they wanted us to go, both Tom and I, to go and form part of this team that they were forming.
There was another gentleman from the University of Wisconsin and another one from Berkeley.
Do you know who they were?
Aaron Horowitz from Berkeley was a housing specialist, old gentleman, very, very capable.
And Ved Prakash was from the University of Wisconsin, and he did the financial analysis.
Ved, V-E-D is his first name, and last name is P-R-A-K-A-S-H, very capable fellow UN expert type and so forth.
And then Aaron Horowitz is from Berkeley, also very respected in the field, H-O-R-O-W-I-T-Z.
Okay, so we spent actually the latter half of 69, I believe the first month of 70 in Colombia working with the Cali General Development Plan.
and reorganize the whole work for them.
And that's why you and I did not meet when I first got here.
Yes.
I arrived in October, one month after the fall semester had begun.
I see, yes.
And I had been invited by Dean Romanek at that time, I think at the request of Joe McGraw.
And what had happened was they were short in architecture.
And so I was invited to guest speak, and that worked out well.
So then I got an invitation to join the faculty the first year in architecture, teaching fifth-year design.
And then they would make room on the planning faculty for me the following year.
So we didn't meet, because you were away in Cali.
Yes, in Colombia, South America.
Very true.
And so then we came back in the spring then of 1970, which you had been here a semester then, and got back into the program.
And of course, as I was telling you earlier, the turmoil that was going on in the world at the time because of the Vietnam War, it spilled over into our own environment here in our own campuses.
And we were in a stage of reconsidering a lot of our policies and priorities and
Jack Kennedy had, of course, established the Peace Corps program, which had generated a lot of interest abroad.
And our kids were coming back with a lot of ideas about what they wanted to do with this world.
And the environmental issue was beginning to heat up, too, the environmental crisis.
The Vista volunteers were beginning to impact the communities where they were.
In other parts of the country, they were having urban riots.
Urban riots, right.
I forget when the Watts riot was.
But I mean, there was just, yeah, everywhere you could think of, Chicago, the Northeast, and so forth, they were having riots.
A lot of turmoil, a lot of unrest.
And that was also affecting the planning programs.
And it seemed like the planning program, because I guess we were a maverick anyway on the campus to begin with.
We kind of broke out of the mold, the more traditional mold here at the university.
We were looked at with some suspicion.
And our students were different.
They did.
I think that that was nationwide.
Yeah, true.
Most of the action on campuses, like at Kent State and Berkeley, really were
instituted by architecture and planning students.
Very much so.
And there were young kids that were concerned with social problems, and the deterioration of our urban environments in the post-war era had not been accomplished.
And they wanted to do things.
They wanted to change this world.
And I guess Kennedy also, John Kennedy, was inspirational in giving some of the spiritual guidance to this.
And then the environmental movement took off, and that certainly became a very powerful moving force.

And so all of that impacted the program, and our students were active, not perhaps certainly as active and demonstrative as the Berkeley students or elsewhere, but they still were raising questions and creating enough interest, you know, that sometimes they worried the administration and so forth.
Yeah, of course, that was during the era of President Johnson's administration.
Yes.
In an era of fantastic social legislation.
That's right.
With the Model Cities program and Office of Economic Opportunities and so forth.
Right.
Because John Kennedy, of course, was a senator in 63, wasn't he?
But his programs continued to...
Were picked up by Johnson.
Right.
And Johnson continued.
That's right.
President Lyndon Johnson, whom, by the way, we met on our honeymoon on the way out to the West Coast by accident there at the... At the ranch?
At the ranch, yeah.
He was driving in with about
10 state governors from around the country that he was having a meeting with there at the Pedernales Ranch.
And so we said hello to him and had a little chat with him.
He was an interesting fellow.
And anyway, of course, we're in the planning program.
We're trying to respond to this concern by young people with the environment of the country, the planning conditions of the country.
And planning was supposed to take a leadership role in influencing policymaking.
So I had, of course, an interest in helping with that.
And a very good background to do it.
Yeah, well, the experience, of course, had been good, yeah, in California and Chile.
And of course, at Harvard, we had also been imbued with similar concerns.
I mean, the same kind of concerns had begun to surface when I was at Harvard, but it hadn't taken off yet.
It was just beginning to start.
And the activism was beginning to take off.
We had some of that.
And of course, I was concerned with trying to establish a professional program that was well-respected and well-recognized and that wasn't frivolous.
Because a lot of it was frivolity, in fact.
And of course, we were also impacted by some of the writings of Davidoff and Reiner, Tom Reiner and Paul Davidoff were talking about
what was it, the choice theory of planning.
Choice theory.
Yeah, and so forth.
And advocacy and all.
The idea of advocacy, of groups doing their own plans.

Well, to me, it was interesting, but at the same time, to me, it created a dilemma, a problem, because if we have a community plan, how can we have a bunch of isolated plans being developed by individualized community groups with their own ideas, what they thought the plan should be, if the whole thing couldn't be brought together?
And that was, in fact, the Achilles heel, so to speak, of the idea.
of that particular concept, you know.
Well, I think at the extreme it led to anarchy in planning.
Yes, exactly.
There was no real official plan that anyone could look to.
That's all you could look for was anarchy, exactly.
It was total chaos and no focus of any kind.

So I had, my concern was trying to incorporate the concept of citizen participation, maximum citizen involvement, certainly work, but working through the elected leadership, because I felt that they were the official representatives of the community that were elected to office, you know.

And so I tried to strike a balance between citizens' involvement and be able to, through surveys and talking to people, having neighborhood community surveys, be able to, in fact, elicit what their concerns were and then introduce those into the community plan and have the leadership accept them because they were well-reasoned and well-developed.
So it was a very interesting period for me to come back from Chile and get into this local environment here.
Of course, we were a small department.
We were a growing department at the time.
I believe we must have had about 30 or 35 students, graduate students.
We were just a graduate program.
With one degree?
One degree, the master's in urban planning.
And we had about how many faculty, Bob?
Let's see, Joe, Jim, yourself, and myself.
Was it Claude Davis?
I don't remember.
I think Claude was teaching in political science, but he taught some of our undergraduate introductory courses.
That's right.
And these were courses that were set up to help introduce the environmental design students in the undergraduate programs to planning who might have an interest in the planning field.
Which never did work.

Well, up to a point in the day, we were able to attract some students, but never really fully integrated, because the whole concept of the environmental design program was not understood really by the department heads at the time that were running it.
Or by the faculty in the other department.

Or the faculty, yeah, because I saw it as a tremendous opportunity for a young student to come into the college and enter as a freshman and maybe explore architecture or landscape architecture or planning or building construction.
or just general environmental design concerns, and then find his or her way eventually into some career focus.
And that this was a much more healthy environment than when I was a freshman because when I was a freshman, it was either architecture or building construction.
You had no other choice.
And if you went too far into any one of those degrees, you would begin to lose credit values because other careers would require other backgrounds.
I felt that this was, and I still think it is a good curriculum to develop properly.

And so our undergraduate courses, we had three or four undergraduate courses, were designed to just explore and expose the students to the field of planning to see if in their graduate work they might pursue it.
And certainly, just as citizens, they could make good use of it.
Oh, yeah.
In any field that they would go into knowing something about what is land use planning or what is zoning and how does it
work and so forth certainly would be useful to anybody in civil engineering or architecture or any other field.
Or just in voting.

Just as a citizen, right, who can make some enlightenment judgments or go to the planning commission or before the planning commission and say a few things about their neighborhood because they know, at least they have a sense of the relationships of their neighborhood to the rest of the city.
So yeah, that was true.
That was important.
So Claude Davis helped us with some of those courses.
He taught partially in political science and partially over here.
Eventually, of course, he was able to transfer over to the planning department and became a full-time member of our faculty.
What courses were you teaching?
I taught laboratories, the planning labs, 601 and 602, usually, were the ones that I taught.
They were urban planning laboratories.
I taught the comprehensive planning course on location.
There wasn't a comprehensive planning course then.
There wasn't?
No.
We had 365, but we didn't have comprehensive planning.
I introduced the comprehensive planning course.
Well, I thought it was already established.
Anyway, when I taught it, I thought I prepared a- 365 you might have taught.
Possibly.
I think that's probably what it was.
We had 665, which became, in fact, the whole place graduate level course.
All I know is that I taught it afterwards.
I would teach sometimes a housing course.
I would ask them to teach the housing course.
And I also taught, well, I was asked to create two courses.
One was planning in the developing countries.
And one was planning 621, which was geared to Latin America.
And then planning 620, which was geared to Latin America plus other parts of the developing world, Africa and Far East.
And those courses were taught again.
They were elective courses that were available to planning students and anybody on campus.
And those became interesting courses because a lot of students took them from around the campus.
And I always had these mixed classes of students in agriculture or engineering or planning.
